But how do I keep the computation efficient while making it obscure? Maybe adding a permutation of the channels before applying LN. So shuffle the channels, apply LN, then unshuffle. That would mix up the information across channels in a non-standard way.

Let me sketch this out:

In the forward pass, after GAP, I take the channel features, permute their order, apply LN, then permute back. Then proceed with the sigmoid and scaling.

This way, the normalization isn't applied per-channel independently anymore; instead, it's considering a shuffled version of the channels, which might lead to different interactions between them.

